@@eThe Sepulchur Pasture: Civic Burial Registry@@N

@@yTemple Liaison Bureau, Funerary Administration Division@@N
@@dFiled under: Deferred Names, Tithe of Last Burdens, Gravebell Incident@@N

This is ours. @@ySepulchur Pasture@@N is where Midgaard buries what it
cannot keep and cannot release. The field where the city's promises
to its dead are @@rtested and found wanting@@N.

Before the name, there was the @@dNinth Acre@@N -- beyond the ninth
milestone, where shepherd-priests rang a bell at dusk. The @@WOath of
Light@@N traces its oldest language to that practice: @@dno ward shall
go unlit@@N. The bell was the first ward-light.

As the city grew, the dead outpaced the living's grief. The city
solved this @@ywith process@@N. Road dead routed to the acre. Names
copied from signet rings. Mercy became a @@ycivic machine@@N.

The @@yTithe of Last Burdens@@N was imposed during the @@rAsh-and-Iron
Decades@@N. Families who could pay bought sanctified plots. Those who
could not were entered as @@d"deferred names"@@N -- interred in common
furrows pending claim. Postponement without deadline is
indistinguishable from abandonment. A quiet industry formed: clerks
charging for corrections, carriers misplacing evidence, brokers
trading inheritance rumor. The Reckoning compiled a @@rregistry of the
registry's failures@@N. It fills two volumes.

When the @@WViolet Compact's@@N containment doctrine spread, certain
remains were forbidden immediate burial. Holding pens, wardwire
trenches, witness lantern circles. The Compact called it safety.
Temple mourners called it trapping souls in limbo. Our Bureau
@@dfiled both objections and implemented the policy@@N.

Then the omen. Night watch heard the @@rgravebell ring twice for every
pull@@N -- once from the tower, once from beneath the furrows. Ledger
irregularities followed: names without bodies, bodies without names,
claim tokens duplicated across unrelated dead. @@d"Deferred name"@@N
stopped meaning paperwork and started meaning @@runrest@@N.

Children in nearby wards still repeat at dusk: @@d"Pay the living,
name the dead, and do not let the bell count twice."@@N

The Continuity faction insists the anomaly has a mechanical
explanation. The Reckoning asks how many generations constitute
@@d"pending."@@N The Bureau maintains the gravebell schedule, inspects
quarterly, and @@rnotes in every report that the second ring has no
identified source@@N.

If the bell counts twice, the ledger has failed. And the dead are
doing their own accounting.
